{"title_page": "List of Austin & Ally episodes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{italic title|string=Austin & Ally}}\n''[[Austin & Ally]]'' is an American [[comedy]] television series created by [[Kevin Kopelow and Heath Seifert]] that aired on [[Disney Channel]] from December 2, 2011 to January 10, 2016. The series stars [[Ross Lynch]], [[Laura Marano]], [[Raini Rodriguez]], and [[Calum Worthy]].\n\n== Series overview ==\n<!-- full linking is used in the following template because it is transcluded to the main series article -->\n\n<onlyinclude>{{Series overview\n\n| color1    = #000000\n| link1     = <includeonly>List of Austin & Ally episodes</includeonly>#Season 1 (2011\u201312)\n| episodes1 = 19\n| start1    = {{Start date|2011|12|2}}\n| end1      = {{End date|2012|9|9}}\n\n| color2    = #FADA5E\n| link2     = <includeonly>List of Austin & Ally episodes</includeonly>#Season 2 (2012\u201313)\n| episodes2 = 26\n| start2    = {{Start date|2012|10|7}}\n| end2      = {{End date|2013|9|29}}\n\n| color3    = #A52A2A\n| link3     = <includeonly>List of Austin & Ally episodes</includeonly>#Season 3 (2013\u201314)\n| episodes3 = 22\n| start3    = {{Start date|2013|10|27}}\n| end3      = {{End date|2014|11|23}}\n\n| color4    = #1034A6\n| link4     = <includeonly>List of Austin & Ally episodes</includeonly>#Season 4 (2015\u201316)\n| episodes4 = 20\n| start4    = {{Start date|2015|1|18}}\n| end4      = {{End date|2016|1|10}}\n\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== Episodes ==\n\n=== Season 1 (2011\u201312) ===\n{{Episode table\n| background      = #000000\n| overall         = 5\n| season          = 6\n| title           = 22\n| titleR          = <ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" /><ref name=\"Zap2it Season 1\" />\n| director        = 13\n| writer          = 19\n| airdate         = 14\n| airdateR        = <ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" /><ref name=\"Zap2it Season 1\" />\n| prodcode        = 10\n| prodcodeR       = <ref name=\"Copyright Office\" /><ref name=\"The Futon Critic\" />\n| viewers         = 11\n| country         = U.S.\n| episodes        = \n\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = Rockers & Writers\n| DirectedBy      = [[Shelley Jensen]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Kevin Kopelow & Heath Seifert]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|12|2}}\n| ProdCode        = 101\n| Viewers         = 5.66<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2011/12/05/fridays-cable-ratings-gold-rush-holds-onto-demo-crown-279213/cable_20111202/|title=Friday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 5, 2011|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Ally Dawson, a shy songwriter, works at ''Sonic Boom'', a music store owned by her father, Lester, located at the Mall of [[Miami]]. Austin Moon, an aspiring singer, interrupts Ally while she is in her practice room, singing a rough cut of \"Double Take\". Unbeknownst to Ally, Austin and his best friend, Dez, accidentally use the song thinking Austin wrote it himself, create a video, and post it on the Internet, after which Austin becomes an Internet sensation. After performing the song on \"The Helen Show\", Helen suggests that Austin returns and performs another original song. Austin isn't good at song-writing, and the only solution he can think of is to plead with Ally to write another song for him. Ally initially denies in anger, but later agrees to help him. The two bond while working on their next song, \"Break Down the Walls\", and Austin asks Ally to be there when he performs it. However, when the pianist gets sick, Ally has to fill in. This was all part of Austin's plan to help Ally overcome her [[stage fright]], but it only ends in disaster. However, Austin and Ally become partners, along with Dez as video director, and Ally's best friend, Trish, as Austin's manager.\n\n''Guest stars'': [[Andy Milder]] as Lester, Mim Drew as Helen\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 2\n| Title           = Kangaroos & Chaos\n| DirectedBy      = Shelley Jensen\n| WrittenBy       = Kevin Kopelow & Heath Seifert\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|12|4}}\n| ProdCode        = 102\n| Viewers         = 3.96<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2011/12/06/sundays-cable-ratings-kourtney-and-kim-claims-demo-crown-for-e-688312/cable_20111204/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 6, 2011|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = It has been one month since Austin's latest song was released; he becomes worried that his career will end and people will forget who he is. Because of this, people are starting to think that Austin is the dog food guy since he looks a lot like the dog food guy in the dog food commercial. Under pressure, Ally scribbles down song lyrics to Austin's new song in illegible handwriting, prompting Trish and Dez to start gathering random props for the music video, such as a kangaroo, which they think correspond to her lyrics. The group quickly works together to resolve the mix-up and Austin performs a new song written by Ally, which successfully regains his fame.\n\n''Guest stars'': Andy Milder as Lester, Andy Goldenberg as Martin, Hollywood Yates as Facepuncher, [[Emily Skinner (actress, born 2002)|Emily Skinner]] as Mad Dog\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 3\n| Title           = Secrets & Songbooks\n| DirectedBy      = Shelley Jensen\n| WrittenBy       = Eric Friedman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2011|12|11}}\n| ProdCode        = 103\n| Viewers         = 3.40<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2011/12/31/sundays-cable-ratings-kourtney-and-kim-tops-demo-charts-581004/cable_20111211/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=December 31, 2011|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Ally loses her songbook, which is also her diary, so she and Trish desperately look for it, unaware that Austin and Dez have already found and read it, discovering that Ally has a secret crush. When Austin is convinced it is him, he tries to find a way to make Ally stop crushing on him and let her know they are just friends. Ally and Trish find out Austin and Dez have read the diary and plan an elaborate scheme for revenge to teach Austin a lesson. Ally reveals that her crush is actually a boy named Dallas ([[Noah Centineo]]) who works at the cell phone accessory cart near Sonic Boom.\n\n''Guest stars'': Cole Sand as Nelson, Carlos Santos as Interviewer\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 4\n| Title           = Zaliens & Cloud Watchers\n| DirectedBy      = Shelley Jensen\n| WrittenBy       = Rick Nyholm\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|1|8}}\n| ProdCode        = 105\n| Viewers         = 2.99<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/01/10/sundays-cable-ratings-kourtney-and-kim-takes-demo-crown-985212/cable_20120108/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 10, 2012|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Ally writes a new song that she is proud of, as it is supposed to be about Austin; however, he hates the song because it is not him at all. The two decide they need to get to know each other better in order for Ally to write songs that will relate to Austin, so they each do activities that the other finds fun. Meanwhile, Trish and Dez, who have never gotten along, surprisingly discover they have things in common. After the horror festival ends in a fiasco, involving Pickles the Goose who helps Ally with her [[writer's block]], Austin and Ally finally decide that although they are different, it's that difference that makes them better partners.\n\n''Guest stars'': Cole Sand as Nelson, Matthew Scott Montgomery as Walter\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 5\n| Title           = Bloggers & Butterflies\n| DirectedBy      = Shelley Jensen\n| WrittenBy       = Heath Seifert & Kevin Kopelow\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|1|15}}\n| ProdCode        = 104\n| Viewers         = 2.81<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/01/18/sundays-cable-ratings-cajun-pawn-stars-kourtney-and-kim-snag-top-spots-159414/cable_20120115/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 18, 2012|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = <!-- Episode summaries must be expressed in your own words. Do NOT submit content you find from another web site as it is plagiarism and likely a copyright violation, which Wikipedia cannot accept and will be removed or reverted. Superficially modifying copyrighted content or closely paraphrasing it, even if the source is cited, still constitutes a copyright violation. Summaries should be about 100 to 200 words in length, per WP:TVPLOT, and those substantially less than 100 words are most likely to be scrutinized for possible copyright violation. -->\n\n''Guest stars'': [[Audrey Whitby]] as Tilly, Cole Sand as Nelson\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 6\n| Title           = Tickets & Trashbags\n| DirectedBy      = [[Adam Weissman]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Samantha Silver & Joey Manderino]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|1|22}}\n| ProdCode        = 107\n| Viewers         = 2.98<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/01/24/sundays-cable-ratings-kourtney-and-kim-housewives-top-demos-250315/cable_20120122/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 24, 2012|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Everyone is excited when Austin is invited to perform at the Miami Internet Music Awards; unfortunately, Austin is only allowed to bring one guest. Everyone's friendship is tested as Ally, Trish, and Dez all compete to win the coveted guest ticket. After Austin accidentally says yes to all of them, they all get upset with him, leaving Austin wondering if he should just go alone. On the night of the awards, Ally, Trish, and Dez realize they have been selfish and show up in disguise to support Austin during his performance.\n\n''Guest stars'': Cole Sand as Nelson, James Earl as Shiny Money\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 7\n| Title           = Managers & Meatballs\n| DirectedBy      = Adam Weissman\n| WrittenBy       = Wayne Conley\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|1|29}}\n| ProdCode        = 108\n| Viewers         = 3.55<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/01/31/sundays-cable-ratings-sag-awards-simulcast-on-par-with-last-year-638510/cable_20120129/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 31, 2012|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Everyone's loyalty is put to the test when Austin is approached by hotshot music manager Demonica Dixon who wants to sign him, promising to take his music career to the next level. Austin is backed into the position of having to choose between his friends and the promise of fame. When Austin learns that Demonica has been purposely sabotaging his friendships with Ally, Trish, and Dez, he sticks with his friends, saying that he doesn't want to be famous without them. In the end, the group gives Demonica a taste of her own medicine.\n\n''Guest star'': [[Lisa Arch]] as Demonica Dixon\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 8\n| Title           = Club Owners & Quincea\u00f1eras\n| DirectedBy      = [[Eric Dean Seaton]]\n| WrittenBy       = Joey Manderino & Samantha Silver\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|2|19}}\n| ProdCode        = 109\n| Viewers         = 3.53<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/22/sundays-cable-ratings-walking-dead-overshadows-the-competition-373512/cable_20120219/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=February 22, 2012|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Trish is having her [[quincea\u00f1era]] and mentions that Emilio, a relative and big-time club owner, will be at her party. Austin decides to perform at Trish's party so he can impress Emilio to book him in his clubs. Trish invites Dallas to her party so that Ally can dance with him. However, since Ally is a horrible dancer she asks Austin to give her dance lessons, but accidentally breaks his leg during a practice. At the party, Ally asks Dallas to dance with her, but he says no to her. Ally becomes upset and doesn't enjoy the rest of the party. During the middle of the party, Dez thinks Austin can swing in on a rope for his grand entrance for his performance. However, they end up wrecking all of Trish's presents. Ally also finds out Dallas said no to her just because he was also a horrible dancer. At the very end of the party, Ally and Dallas find out they have much in common and connect with each other by dancing. When Emilio shows up, the group finds out Emilio doesn't own night clubs, but he owns country clubs.\n\n''Guest stars'': Eileen Galindo as Trish's Mom, Devan Leos as J.J.\n| LineColor       = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 9\n| Title           = Deejays & Demos\n| DirectedBy      = [[Roger Christiansen]]\n| WrittenBy       = Steve Freeman & Aaron Ho\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2012|2|26}}\n| ProdCode        = 111\n| Viewers         = 2.73<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/ratings/2012/02/28/sundays-cable-ratings-nba-all-star-game-sneaks-past-the-walking-dead-458415/cable_20120226/|title=Sunday's Cable Ratings|publisher=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=February 28, 2012|access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = <!-- Epi